A text-processing utility class called RepeatChecker analyzes strings and sentences for consecutive repeated characters. Two adjacent characters form a "consecutive repeat" if they are identical—for example, the "ll" in "hello" or the "ee" in "sweet".

The following is a partial class declaration.

public class RepeatChecker {

    /** Returns true if text contains at least one pair of consecutively
     *  identical characters, false otherwise.
     *  Precondition: text is not null.
     */
    public boolean hasConsecutiveRepeat(String text)
    { /* to be implemented in part (a) */ }

    /** Returns the number of space-separated words in sentence for which
     *  hasConsecutiveRepeat returns true.
     *  Precondition: sentence contains at least one word with no leading
     *  or trailing spaces.
     */
    public int countRepeatWords(String sentence)
    { /* to be implemented in part (b) */ }
}

reference_solution:
public class RepeatChecker {
    public boolean hasConsecutiveRepeat(String text) {
        for (int i = 0; i < text.length() - 1; i++) {
            if (text.substring(i, i + 1).equals(text.substring(i + 1, i + 2))) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }

    public int countRepeatWords(String sentence) {
        int count = 0;
        while (sentence.length() > 0) {
            int spaceIdx = sentence.indexOf(" ");
            String word;
            if (spaceIdx == -1) {
                word = sentence;
                sentence = "";
            } else {
                word = sentence.substring(0, spaceIdx);
                sentence = sentence.substring(spaceIdx + 1);
            }
            if (hasConsecutiveRepeat(word)) {
                count++;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
}

